SIMPLE: omentum
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Omentum
<hw>O*men"tum</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Omenta</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>
<def>A free fold of the peritoneum, or one serving to connect viscera,
support blood vessels, etc.; an epiploon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>great</xex>, or <xex>gastrocolic</xex>,
<xex>omentum</xex> forms, in most mammals, a great sac, which is
attached to the stomach and transverse colon, is loaded with fat, and
covers more or less of the intestines; the caul. The <xex>lesser</xex>,
or <xex>gastrohepatic</xex>, <xex>omentum</xex> connects the stomach and
liver and contains the hepatic vessels. The <stype>gastrosplenic
omentum</stype>, or <xex>ligament</xex>, connects the stomach and
spleen.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Omer</ent>⟦br⟧
